Certainly! Here's an example of how to automatically generate a table of contents in a LaTeX document. This example includes the necessary commands and demonstrates the structure of a basic document with chapters and sections:

```latex
\documentclass[12pt,a4paper]{report}

% Packages
\usepackage[utf8]{inputenc}
\usepackage[T1]{fontenc}
\usepackage{hyperref}

% Document title, author, and date
\title{Example Document with Table of Contents}
\author{Your Name}
\date{\today}

\begin{document}

% Generate title page
\maketitle

% Generate table of contents
\tableofcontents
\newpage

% Start of the document content
\chapter{Introduction}
\section{Background}
This is the background section of the introduction.

\section{Objectives}
These are the objectives of the document.

\chapter{Methodology}
\section{Data Collection}
This section describes the data collection process.

\section{Data Analysis}
This section outlines the data analysis techniques used.

\chapter{Results}
\section{Main Findings}
Here are the main findings of the study.

\section{Discussion}
This section discusses the implications of the results.

\chapter{Conclusion}
\section{Summary}
This is a summary of the document.

\section{Future Work}
This section suggests areas for future research.

% End of the document
\end{document}
```

In this example:

1. We use the `report` document class, which is suitable for longer documents with chapters.

2. We include some basic packages: `inputenc` for input encoding, `fontenc` for font encoding, and `hyperref` for creating clickable links in the table of contents.

3. We set the document title, author, and date using `\title`, `\author`, and `\date` commands.

4. The `\maketitle` command generates the title page.

5. The `\tableofcontents` command automatically generates the table of contents based on the document structure.

6. We use `\chapter` and `\section` commands to create the document structure. LaTeX will automatically number these and include them in the table of contents.

7. The `\newpage` command after the table of contents ensures that the content starts on a new page.

When you compile this LaTeX document, it will automatically generate a table of contents that includes all chapters and sections, with correct page numbers. The table of contents will be placed after the title page and before the main content.

Remember that you may need to compile the document twice to get the correct page numbers in the table of contents, as LaTeX needs one run to determine the page numbers and another to update the table of contents.

